description:
In 2014, two young Dutch girls set out on a 6-week trip of a lifetime to Panama. But one day, the girls went on a spontaneous hike and never returned to their host familys house. Ten weeks later, a backpack was discovered that only made the girls disappearances that much more mysterious. In this episode, we try to solve the mystery of the deaths of Kris Kremers and Lisanne Froon.

comments.text: Im sorry the way the significant 6.2 earthquake (see time stamp;49:35) was seemingly glossed over is insane! An earthquake of that magnitude, even at such a distance, would be undeniably terrifying, especially in the heart of a mountainous jungle. Not to mention the far-reaching environmental effects that inevitably follow. The potential for injury alone from the earthquake should not be underestimated; it could have exacerbated their stress and possibly disoriented them if they werent already. Based solely on the information provided in this podcast, it strongly suggests that one of them may have sustained injuries after the April 2nd earthquake while initially and intentionally venturing beyond the designated trail's endpoint.

comments.text: In 8th grade, my class took a hiking trip to a local forest area with a spot everyone called the Pinnacle bc it was a very high hilltop spot to view the town and surrounding areas. Its a beautiful spot. Even though most of the kids in my class had been on these trails, we, as a group, got completely lost. We were supposed to be back at school by 3pm for bus pickup but we didnt make out of the woods until 5pm. Fortunately no one was injured and afterwards we laughed it off. The point is that is SO incredibly easy to get lost in the woods even if you are experienced or familiar with the area.

comments.text: Oh my... as an experienced hiker. I think they got lost... Limited resources, limited light (daylight only to move), unknown location, dense forest coverage, and animal track trails. Those are SOS attempts to get them located/PU. I've been lost ONCE. Simply for walking off path to take a few pictures. That desperation is there from the girls with the calls, but conservation is a must. They had no water and no extra food. They had 16 Oz to last how many days??? That is an instant X, unless you have a filtering aid. I've been in a "no service" area, but when the right satellite rolls by, your phone will light up with notifications from calls, texts, apps, etc. That's speaking from experience. Storms will even interfere with service. God rest their souls. I pray for peace and healing for their families.

comments.text: Another thing to note is that rainforests are literal ovens. The high humidity plus the heat makes it unbearably hot. People think deserts are hotter. If the girls did pass away, their bodies would be completely decomposed within a week and their remains would be scattered and nearly skeletalized. I really hope the family get some type of closure. I cant imagine the pain they are dealing with.

comments.text:
I definitely think the girls succumbed to the elements in some way. Perhaps one or both were injured or there was an accident, who knows. But I dont think foul play was involved.

Often in mysterious cases like these I think people get caught up in the mystery and the unknown and we want it to be more than it is. But we know that more often than not theres a straight forward explanation. We just dont have all the information necessary to have that explanation in this case. 

I also think that people, especially those of us who have never been in an environment like the jungle or have never spent much time out in nature in general, severely discount how inhospitable this environment truly is. The indigenous peoples of this area have had millennia to adapt to living there. A tourist is going to be wildly out of their depth there. Even if you have mountaineering experience the jungle is a unique beast that requires specialized knowledge and experience. I think theres also a phenomenon with tourists where we may not take things as seriously as we should because we have a mindset of nothing bad can happen on vacation. I think the girls probably bit off a bit more than they could chew and were exhausted, hungry, thirsty, scared and confused. They made poor choices because of these factors and their overall lack of knowledge and that got them into a bad situation. Combine that with Panamanian authorities lack of quick action and I think its pretty clear how this could happen.

I truly do feel for these girls. I cant imagine how scary this experience was and how horrible it must have been to die out there alone and afraid not knowing if your family would ever find you or know what happened to you. I feel for their families and I understand clinging to the idea of foul play. I think it gives a little hope that someone out there knows what happened to them. I think the pain of not knowing is absolutely brutal and I completely understand clinging to any shred of hope you can find.

I pray both of these girls souls are resting easy and peacefully now. I pray their families find peace and happiness. May their memories be a blessing

To tackle that point, I think before the other calls they had their phones up and out looking for signal after the first "112" attempts, walking around for some time trying to get more bars, and then later made the decision to conserve battery. 

The reason there's such a broad space of time between the emergency call attempts to me comes off as: when you're in a forest or jungle, on a logical scale, when do you think you'll have the best chance for signal? In clearings, open spaces, less dense areas, etc. I wonder if they were conserving battery and the only attempted to make those calls when they reached a less dense area of the jungle thinking that was their best chance at getting signal, and when they didn't, turned off their phones again and kept going until they reached another open/less dense area. It would explain the large gaps between the calls and the attempts at only dialing out once. The failed calls confirmed they had no signals to them even with 1 bar, and that's all they needed to decide to turn off the phones again. 

I think Josh was slightly misunderstanding that she wasn't talking that they were in the same spot trying to make multiple calls, but that a normal reaction would have been to have their phones up and out and attempt calls every few mins as they continued walking, rather than just go hours between phone call attempts.
